const v18ReadA={id:"v18-read-a",kind:"passage",label:"Passage for Items 69-72",title:"Medicine Delivery Loggers",description:"A rural health network delivered temperature-sensitive medicine in insulated boxes. Drivers recorded departure and arrival temperatures, but the records could not show when a temperature excursion occurred during a six-hour trip. The network added electronic loggers that recorded every ten minutes and placed one probe beside the medicine rather than near the ice pack. Data showed repeated warming during long unloading stops. Routes were reorganized and boxes stayed closed until the receiving worker was ready. Excursions declined, although the network continued biological-quality checks because temperature history alone did not directly measure medicine potency.",alt:"Passage about medicine deliveries improved by ten-minute temperature loggers, correct probe placement, route changes, and closed boxes, while retaining separate potency checks."};
const v18ReadB={id:"v18-read-b",kind:"passage",label:"Babasahin para sa Aytem 73-76",title:"Mas Bukas na Pulong sa Badyet",description:"Kaunti ang dumadalo sa konsultasyon sa badyet na laging ginagawa tuwing hapon sa munisipyo. Sa panayam, sinabi ng ilang magulang na wala silang mapag-iiwanan ng bata, samantalang ang mga manggagawa sa malalayong barangay ay hindi nakaaabot bago magsara ang biyahe. Sinubukan ng bayan ang isang pulong sa Sabado, naglaan ng child-friendly waiting area, at nagbukas ng sabayang online at telephone comments. Dumami at naging mas iba-iba ang kalahok. Gayunman, hindi itinuring na awtomatikong kinatawan ng buong bayan ang mga dumalo; inihambing pa rin ang kanilang barangay at sektor sa kabuuang populasyon.",alt:"Teksto tungkol sa konsultasyon sa badyet na binago ang oras at access channels, nagdagdag ng child-friendly area, dumami ang kalahok, ngunit sinuri pa rin kung kinatawan sila ng buong bayan."};
const v18ReadC={id:"v18-read-c",kind:"passage",label:"Passage for Items 77-80",title:"Pedestrian Signal Timing",description:"A transport office received complaints that older adults could not finish crossing a wide avenue before the signal changed. Engineers measured walking time for a varied sample, including people using canes and wheelchairs, and separated waiting time from crossing time. They lengthened the pedestrian phase and added an audible countdown at two test intersections. In the pilot, incomplete crossings fell, while vehicle delay rose slightly. Officials planned to compare safety gains, accessibility, and traffic effects before expanding the change instead of treating vehicle speed as the only performance measure.",alt:"Passage about measuring diverse pedestrian crossing times, extending signals, adding audible countdowns, reducing incomplete crossings, and balancing safety and access with traffic delay."};
